ce:section.ce:para:
The fluorometric sulfide detection based on CD/Ag+ probe and spectrophotometric based on Ag+ ion in solution are compared in Fig. 10
                        . It is clear that the dynamic range of fluorometry shifts to a lower concentration range as compared with spectrophotometric. In fact, at low concentration of sulfide ion, there is no measurable change in the absorbance of Ag2S solution while there is a significant decrease in the fluorescence intensity of CD/Ag+. This improvement in the detection of limit and dynamic response range caused by IFEs can be explained by this fact that the absorbance changes of the absorber are exponentially converted into the fluorescence changes of the fluorophore [43]. In addition, the linear range and detection limit of various recently published optical methods are compared with those of our work (Table 1
                        ). From the table, sulfide detection based on CD/Hg2+ and CD/Ag+ have the sensitivity higher or comparable with many of these reports, although there are some reports with higher sensitivities. However, the proposed probes need no expensive materials or complicated probe preparation and provide a simple and easy assays.
